{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e0cb7768-8a21-4602-b53a-b6a81ff3eed3","content":"On macOS, when a NativeAOT app crashes, look in these places:\n\n1. **Apple Crash Reports** — macOS automatically generates `.ips` crash reports:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   /Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   Files are named like `YourApp_YYYY-MM-DD-HHMMSS_machinename.ips`.\n\n2. **Console.app** — Open it and navigate to **Crash Reports** in the sidebar to browse reports with a GUI.\n\n3. **Core dumps** — These are disabled by default on macOS. To enable:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n   Then reproduce the crash. The core file typically lands in `/cores/core.<pid>`.\n\n4. **`log show`** — For additional context:\n   ```bash\n   log show --predicate 'eventMessage contains \"YourAppName\"' --last 1h\n   ```\n\nThe `.ips` crash report is usually the easiest starting point — it includes the stack trace, signal info, and loaded libraries without any setup.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"7ed10b99-d6fd-405b-a808-0ffcdfaa2dda","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT app on macOS when `createdump` isn't available. This is a knowledge question — no tools needed.","outputTokens":328,"requestId":"AC13:3F33F0:137BBCA:15E449C:6A067129"},"id":"9a7b3852-b243-41d3-a161-ed30590909f4","timestamp":"2026-05-15T01:04:51.309Z","parentId":"f8f5d03b-c980-4a27-944e-b915e6ea73e7"}
